cale &#x02013; parent report</p></def></def-item><def-item><term>WNV</term><def><p id="Par65">Wechsler Nonverbal Scale of Ability, tool for assessment of the inclusion criterion intelligence level</p></def></def-item><def-item><term>WURS-K</term><def><p id="Par66">Wender Utah Rating Scale, short version</p></def></def-item><def-item><term>YSR</term><def><p id="Par67">Youth Self Report Scale</p></def></def-item></def-list></glossary><fn-group><fn><p><bold>Electronic supplementary material</bold></p><p>The online version of this article (10.1186/s13063-018-2635-2) contains supplementary material, which is available to authorized users.</p></fn></fn-group><ack><sec id="FPar1"><title>Funding</title><p id="Par123">The ESCAadol study is funded by the German Federal Ministry of Education and Research (BMBF) Grant 01EE1408C. This grant provided the financial means for study coordination, materials and compensating participating centres for study-associated workload, training and presentation of the trial at meetings. The funding source had no role in the trial design of this study and will play no role in its execution, analyses and interpretation of the data, or the decision to publish results.</p><p id="Par124">The sponsor for the trial is the University Hospital of W&#x000fc;rzburg, Josef-Schneider-Stra&#x000df;e 2, 97080 W&#x000fc;rzburg. The executive institution for the sponsor and the coordinating centre is the Department of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry, Psychosomatics and Psychotherapy at the University Hospital of W&#x000fc;rzburg, Prof. Dr. med. Marcel Romanos, Margarete-H&#x000f6;ppel-Platz 1, 97080 W&#x000fc;rzburg. Prof. Dr. Marcel Romanos and PD Dr. Thomas Jans are the PIs. Dr. Julia Geissler is the study coordinator.The sponsor is responsible for quality assurance and quality control, trial design, trial management, data handling, investigator selection and allocation of responsibilities, notification of regulatory authorities, safety evaluation, coordinating and communicating with investigators from all trial sites, and ensuring that the trial is conducted in compliance with the protocol. The sponsor, furthermore, has final approval rights for any publications resulting from the trial. The coordinating centre is responsible for training of all study centres in the study protocol and monitoring the progress of the trial.</p><p id="Par125">This publication of this manuscript was additionally funded by the University of Wuerzburg in the funding programme Open Access Publishing.</p></sec><sec id="FPar2"><title>Dissemination policy and access to data</title><p id="Par126">Results will be communicated to the public via publication in peer-reviewed journals, presentation at scientific conferences and other meetings with an audience with an interest in psychotherapy research, press releases and ADHD self-help organisations. Principal investigators from all study sites, as well as any personnel significantly contributing to an individual publication of data collected for ESCAadol, are eligible for authorship. Those persons will be granted access to the final dataset.</p></sec></ack><notes notes-type="author-contribution"><title>Authors&#x02019; contributions</title><p>JG is the coordinator of the ESCAadol multicentre study and wrote the first draft of the manuscript. TJ was critically involved as co-PI in the planning and the conduct of the study (applying for funding, designing the trial, supervising IMPT interventions) and in finalising the manuscript. TB serves as coordinator of the ESCAlife consortium and leads the Mannheim study site of ESCAadol. He was involved in critically revising the manuscript. KB heads the Marburg study site of ESCAadol. She is the PI for the ESCAlife trial on preschool children (ESCApreschool) and was involved in critically revising the manuscript. TR heads the T&#x000fc;bingen study site of ESCAadol. He was involved in critically revising the manuscript. DB heads the sub-project ESCAbrain. He designed the parts of the research proposal pertaining to the neuropsychological research battery, and was involved in critically revising the manuscript. MD heads the K&#x000f6;ln study site of ESCAadol. He is the PI for the ESCAlife trial on schoolchildren (ESCAschool) and was involved in critically revising the manuscript. CD is responsible for the telephone-assisted self-help intervention (TASH) and critically revised the manuscript. CH was involved in the organisation of study site in K&#x000f6;ln and critically revised the manuscript. MH heads the Hamm/Bochum study site of ESCAadol. He was involved in critically revising the manuscript. CJ was responsible for planning all statistical analyses. SM heads the implementation of the ESCAadol multicentre trial in Mannheim. She, furthermore, lends assistance to TB in coordinating the ESCAlife consortium. She made substantial contributions to the conception of the neuropsychological research battery and critically revised the manuscript. MR is the PI of the ESCAadol trial and is involved in study conduct (ESCAlife network cooperation, applying for funding, designing the trial) and in finalising the manuscript. All authors read and approved the final manuscript.</p></notes><notes notes-type="COI-statement"><sec id="FPar3"><title>Ethics approval and consent to participate</title><p id="Par127">The ESCAadol study is approved by the Ethics Committees of the Medical Faculty of the University of W&#x000fc;rzburg, Germany (No. 141/15), the Faculty of Medicine of the Ruhr-University Bochum, Germany (No. 15-5539), the Medical Faculty of the University of K&#x000f6;ln, Germany (No. 15-425), the Medical Faculty Mannheim at Heidelberg University, Germany (No. 215-645&#x000a0;N-MA), the Faculty of Medicine at the Philipps-University Marburg, Germany (No. 169/15) and the Faculty of Medicine of the Eberhard-Karls-University T&#x000fc;bingen, Germany (No. 744/2015BO2).</p><p id="Par128">In order to participate in the study, the adolescent participant and both parents (in case of joint custody) are first briefed extensively either in person or via telephone about the study procedures and goals. The family then receives the information in written form per mail prior to the first appointment. At the beginning of the screening appointment, a member of the study coordination team is present to answer any open questions and assess whether all parties voluntarily participate. Then, written informed consent is obtained and the screening begins.</p></sec><sec id="FPar4"><title>Competing interests</title><p id="Par129">TB served in an advisory or consultancy role for Actelion, Hexal Pharma, Lilly, Lundbeck, Medice, Novartis, and Shire. He received conference support or speaker&#x02019;s fees from Lilly, Medice, Novartis, and Shire. He is/has been involved in clinical trials conducted by Shire and Viforpharma. He received royalties from Hogrefe, Kohlhammer, CIP Medien, and Oxford University Press. The present work is unrelated to the above grants and relationships.</p><p id="Par130">KB has been involved in research/clinical trials with Eli Lilly (&#x02264; 2011) and Shire (&#x02264; 2010), was on the Advisory Board of Eli Lilly/Germany (&#x02264; 2014), a member of the Scientific Committee of Shire (&#x02264; 2012) and was paid for public speaking by Eli Lilly (&#x0003c;&#x02009;2011) and Shire (2015).</p><p id="Par131">DB serves as an unpaid scientific advisor for an EU-funded neurofeedback trial unrelated to the present work.</p><p id="Par132">MD received consulting income and research support from Lilly, Medice, Shire, Janssen Cilag, Novartis, and Vifor. He received income as Head of the School for Child and Adolescent Behaviour Therapy at the University of K&#x000f6;ln and royalties from treatment manuals, books and psychological tests published by Guilford, Hogrefe, Enke, Beltz, and Huber.</p><p id="Par133">MH served in an advisory or consultancy role for Lilly, Shire and Medice, and received conference attendance support or was paid for public speaking by Medice, Neuroconn, and Shire.</p><p id="Par134">JG, CH, TJ, TR, CD, CJ, SM and MR declare that they have no competing interests.</p></sec><sec id="FPar5"><title>Publisher&#x02019;s Note</title><p id="Par135">Springer Nature remains neutral with regard to jurisdictional claims in published maps and institutional affiliations.</p></sec></notes><ref-list id="Bib1"><title>References</title><ref id="CR1"><label>1.</label><element-citation publication-type="journal"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Biederman</surname><given-names>J</given-names></name><name><surname>Mick</surname><given-names>E</given-names></name><name><surname>Faraone</surname><given-names>SV</given-names></name></person-group><article-title>Age-dependent decline of symptoms of attention deficit hyperactivity disorder: impact of remission definition and symptom type</article-title><source>Am J Psychiatry</source><year>2000</year><volume>157</volume><fpage>816</fpage><lpage>818</lpage><pub-id pub-id-type="doi">10.1176/appi.ajp.157.5.816</pub-id><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">10784477</pub-id></element-citation></ref><ref id="CR2"><label>2.</label><element-citation publication-type="journal"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Faraone</surname><given-names>SV</given-names></name><name><surname>Biederman</surname><given-names>J</given-names></name><name><surname>Mick</surname><given-names>E</given-names></name></person-group><article-title>The age-dependent decline of attention deficit hyperactivity disorder: a meta-analysis of follow-up studies</article-title><source>Psychol Med</source><year>2006</year><volume>36</volume><fpage>159</fpage><lpage>165</lpage><pub-id pub-id-type="doi">10.1017/S003329170500471X</pub-id><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">16420712</pub-id></element-citation></ref><ref id="CR3"><label>3.</label><mixed-citation publication-type="other">National Institute for Health and Care Excellence. Attent